The argument extracts the part of a match that was captured with the specified [capturing group][1]. 

See the [docs][2]:

&gt; `regexp_extract(str, regexp[, idx]) - Extracts a group that matches regexp.`&lt;br/&gt;
&gt; **Examples:**&lt;br/&gt;
&gt; `&gt; SELECT regexp_extract(&#39;100-200&#39;, &#39;(\d+)-(\d+)&#39;, 1);`&lt;br/&gt;
&gt; `100`

The `100` substring is captured with the first `(\d+)` in the regex pattern, and the `1` argument makes the function return just this part of the whole match (which is `100-200`).

  [1]: https://www.regular-expressions.info/brackets.html
  [2]: https://people.apache.org/~pwendell/spark-nightly/spark-master-docs/latest/api/sql/index.html#regexp_extract

